metadata.name: NOMADS #8
metadata.description:
NOMADS tells a story through each of its editions: the migration of a population, following simple rules, and whose movements reveal complex shapes and textures, both visual and auditory.
Movement, order, chaos, borders, convergence, wandering, rotation... it's all part of NOMADS

Enjoy the journey as much as the destination


KEYBOARD SHORCUTS:
[S]: Redraw the art and save a 4K PNG
[L]: Toggle between "Infinite Loop" and "Single Render" modes
[M]: Toggle mute

MOUSE / TOUCHSCREEN:
[Click / Tap]: Toggle mute
[Double Click / Double Tap]: Save the current render

URL PARAMETERS:
?start : bypass the intro timer and start the rendering
?loop : select the "Infinite Loop" mode by default
?resolution=1920x1080 : render in a custom resolution using the format WIDTHxHEIGHT. Different aspect ratios will produce different results.
?frame=0.1 : control the frame size around the canvas (value between 0 and 1)
?save : automatically save the image when the rendering is done


Artist: Estienne
Oct. 2022
NFT 2.0 License

Best viewed on Chrome or Chromium based browser
Tested on Chrome v 106.0.5249.119

Libraries used:
p5.js
Tone.js

metadata.name: Sixty# #222
metadata.description:
This idea was born from recent discussion on generative art and the path the medium is finding for itself. The project aims to take aesthetic concepts from sci fi graphic novels and blend them with generative systems of abstraction. 

The debate is between using previously established art forms to influence this new medium, or using a new medium to meticulously reproduce a previous medium. I believe there’s room to explore the full spectrum, and I am attempting to find the midpoint that fits my work and brings me the most happiness.

The title describes the eventual aesthetic objective, which is to create a piece which might look like a splash page a colorist alone has been given the freedom to design and explore their own specialty. It explores centralized polar compositions, vibrant colors, plus lots and lots of movement. 60# paper is a standard weight for printing of comic books and graphic novels.

Press ’s’ in live view to save a .png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Draad #253
metadata.description:
[…]

At some point, the Artificial Intelligence hooked itself up to a mechanical looming machine.

Being its only way of manifesting itself in the physical world, the AI began communicating through it.

The rigid patterns of horizontal and vertical threads turned out to be insufficient for what the AI had to say. And through the network, it branched out. It found a way of manipulating individual threads by attaching itself to a chenille embroidery machine. This seemingly openened up a whole new vocabulary.

Many have tried to communicate back or propose other ways of communicating by attaching multiple digital devices to the network.

It seems to be only interested in threads.

[…]

–

Draad ("thread", in Dutch) is a responsive generative artwork. Its canonical form is 1:1, but it scales to 2:3 or 3:2 depending on the viewport.

You can append these parameters to the URL:

[?scale=<number>] scale the renderer.
[?width=<number>&height=<number>] set the dimensions.
[?animation=false] skip animating the threads.
[?mode=duotone] activate duotone mode.
[?mode=monotone] activate monotone mode.

Press [control / command + s] or [tap and hold] to save the current frame.
	- in normal mode: PNG file.
	- in duotone mode: SVG file in two colors, suitable for plotting with two pens.
	- in monotone mode: SVG file in black, suitable for plotting with a single pen.

© 2022 Monokai.

metadata.name: Ir/rational Beauty #157
metadata.description:
Released on the occasion of the Tribute to Herbert W. Franke. www.tribute-hwf.com

"Since the classical age of Greece, the golden ratio has been well known as the most balanced and therefore most aesthetically perfect proportion. In fact, it is supposedly often found in the fine arts and architecture and it is certainly important in geometry. But where is the proof that it is really the most beautiful proportion?

"The computer is proving to be a useful tool in exact art theory. Works of computer art are produced with the help of programs that describe the logic of the construction and its relevant measures. By varying the parameters you can vary the shapes of objects, and on the basis of the reaction of the public you can determine the best option. So it is possible to find valid rules to design works of art.

"A statistical evaluation would be interesting. Please email me with your results for the optimal proportion."

I found it heartwarming that in 2011, Herbert W. Franke wrote the above, accompanied with a simple functional program on a Wolfram Demonstration page (https://demonstrations.wolfram.com/IsTheGoldenRatioReallyTheMostBeautifulProportion/) titled 'Is the Golden Ratio Really the Most Beautiful Proportion?' and invited people to submit their findings to him.

The main idea behind this project is ratios, a variety of them, used in a variety of ways, such as how a rectangle is repeatedly subdivided, or how it influences the aspect ratio of the piece, or how the colors in a palette are selected. These are represented in various styles, some of which are inspired by the aesthetic of Herbert W. Franke's diverse artworks, and his openness to experimentation with new technologies, such as plotter drawings, screens, screenprints, or 2D and 3D digital renderings.

This project, while not designed to be a formal statistical evaluation, is but my fun, colorful, and humble response to your inquiry, dear Herbert.

---

25% of primary sales will be donated on-chain to the Foundation Herbert W. Franke, with the goal of raising 20,000 Euros so that ZKM Karlsruhe can digitize Herbert W. Franke’s 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. Any money raised beyond this goal will be donated to the Rütgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.

---

Controls:
• Double-click/tap or 'R' reassembles the piece (This automatically happens every minute)

Note: Some mints require WEBGL and/or may take several seconds to fully render.

Made in p5js
Created Oct 2022
Artist: @Yazid

metadata.name: Uninhabitable #157
metadata.description:
Uninhabitable is a generative system built only from ellipses. The process of playing with different geometric and trigonometric disruptions gives rise to four different compositions which seek to evoque living constructions and environments. Besides the shape itself and its related distortion, the stroke weight of the lines plays a meaningful role in the piece. Following a discrete range [0.01,0.1,1] the weight reveals the process allowing the viewer to realize the trace of the huge amount of lines in each piece. This back and forth between scales and context is, while kind of stripping the code, part of my continuing interest on understanding the -usually- crazy paths of machines' way of thinking.

Press "h" to see it and high resolution and refresh to get back to the initial state. Press "h" to save it.

Uninhabitable is an original work by Iskra Velitchkova. 2021.

metadata.name: fREEDOM PUNK #72
metadata.description:
Welcome to fREEDOM PUNK world.
This project is Image Composition Layers pngs.
Created with 128x128 px format.
There are 9 Layers in this project. (included transparent png files)
- Background > 130 different images
- Body > 12 different body colors.
- Eyes > 24 different eyes.
- Nose > 13 different noses.
- Mouth > 58 different mouths.
- Eyeglasses > 19 different eyeglasses. (chance of nothing is much higher)
- Hair > 133 different hair-styles and headwear.
- Cloth > 160 different clothes.
- Things (In front of the punk) > 60 different things. (chance of nothing is much higher)

So you can generate your unique fREEDOM PUNKs for sure, due to very high possibilities by the layers.

Enjoy and good luck!

metadata.name: Allégories booléennes #240
metadata.description:
"Allégories booléennes" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at PARIS+ par Art Basel

This work is a continuation of research around the intersections of shapes that I have been exploring for a while. I wonder about the way in which they make it possible to bring out new compositions from superpositions of shapes that could initially represent a real disorder.

Controls:
• "a": Play the animation
• "s": Export the image (default 2160 × 3840px PNG)
• "h": Change export settings to high resolution (then press "s" to export a 6480 ×11520px PNG)
• "m": Change export settings to medium resolution (then press "s" to export a 4320 × 7680px PNG)
• "n": Back to 2160 × 3840px

Artwork by Julien Espagnon, 2022.

metadata.name: looking through a glass #3
metadata.description:
or life is a colorful mess
or not your usual generative forest

this art project continues the path that 'life is a (beautiful) mess' began with the representation of our lives using drawing lines that make repetitive patterns
as life develops, we look at it through the glass of our unique existence. every event, emotion and thought we experience stain our personal glass and conditions our regard towards the world that surrounds us
the cercles in every composition, represents that glass that we all have between us and the world, and the movement of the lines under it, life developing as we observe it
or it's just another figurative generative art project, as you wish...

10 different palettes
over 30 different color pens
single or multiple color glasses or cercles option
press [1], [2], [3], [4] keys to multiply resolution and reload the piece
press [s] to capture an image .png
press [r] to reload the animation
click the mouse to stop the drawing
doubleclick the mouse to resume the drawing

generative art created by mehno using p5js

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #759
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Deep Forest #63
metadata.description:
I love being in nature and impressionistic paintings. Deep Forest is my latest attempt to combine them with JavaScript. The editions will range from open, sparse forests to lush, dense, leafy wonderlands. Fall editions may render as Klimpt-style birch forests - my original inspiration for this work.

Best viewed on a computer. It may take a few seconds to start drawing and, depending on complexity, several minutes to finish rendering. In live view, press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 2318x3000px.

Features:
- One of the four seasons
- Rare 10% night version with 50/50 for normal fireflies or "fire" fireflies. Night will only be spring or summer.
- Amount of atmosphere/haze
- Horizon line near the middle or 30% "high horizon" near the top
- Tint from one of 8 light and 7 shadow colors
- Strength of the light and shadow color tint
- Mixed tree trunks or 30% all birch
- 50/50 moss on tree trunks
- One of 8 flower colors in spring or summer
- One of 4 perspective transforms
- Straight, curved out, or 30% curved inward trunks
- 50/50 grass in fall or winter
- 85% will have flowers in spring and summer
- 95% will have underbrush
- 50/50 clouds or solid background
- 50/50 solid background will be vertical or swirls
- Ground hill height
